{"text": "The colors, the art, the setting and the lore are spectacular. The voice acting is also very good. Deeply based on religious iconography and themes while being cautious of crossing the line,  â€™ unsettling mood and painstaking detail to everything visual will stay with you for a long time. This is a pixel-art game that fully exploits modern hardware and design, thankfully moving away from the lazy trend of blurry 2D games in imitation of those primitive 8-bit-era graphics that today look dated and dysfunctional. The player character, known only as the Penitent One, is a taciturn creature with little personality but what he lacks in dialogue is compensated by the rich explanations provided by NPCs and in-game elements. Movement is fluid and responsive, and combos are satisfying and finishers gruesomely rewarding, but there is little variation. The combat feeling is solid. The difficulty is moderately hard, but fair. It will gradually become easier once you understand the mechanics of enemies. This is not a game where button mashing will get you very far. I strongly recommend the use of a gamepad. I played with the XBox One wireless controller, which is fully supported. I did not encounter a single bug or glitch. A small but very important detail that I liked a lot is that the game teaches you its mechanics in a smooth way, slowly as you progress through the first stages. No enemy or monster is introduced without proper warning, and the very first of its kind that you see allows for observation and experimentation without too much nearby danger. This is the way all games should be madeâ€”no need for dedicated, irrelevant, boring and lengthy tutorials. There's lots to see and discover, and this is a game to enjoy and take your time to observe. The art is fantastic, and it is seamlessly integrated with the game's mechanics. You might end up wanting to know more about the bizarre enemies, strange locations and intriguing NPCs. Yet, if you want to savor  , there will be a moderate amount of reading involved. Some fragments of lore are a bit confusing, but worth your attention if you are looking to complete all quests or hunt for achievements. Backtracking is abundant, but I found the process not as tiresome or tedious as some other people refer. Mainly because it is a pleasure to see again those gorgeous backgrounds and art, and change the setting every now and then. One thing that must be applauded is that the game manages to keep the sense of discovery fresh. Each new area is as impressive as the last.  is a game that rewards experimentation and curiosity, but it also punishes them in the same measureâ€”an intriguing component definitely in line with the theme of penance and suffering.  I don't know about \"metroidvanias\" of yore since I never played them, but another comparison that usually arises is to Dark Souls. Yes, some elements are similar, like the endless cycle of death and rebirth, learning along the way, but   is not as hard or frustrating. Upon dying all items are kept, but the performance of the Penitent One will decrease until you recover your soul at the place of your demise. This mechanic keeps things interesting while adding another layer of simple strategy. The bosses are impressive and varied, likely to pose a challenge to the unprepared. In the end, like the game itself, they can be defeated by learning the patterns and skillfully dodging their attacks. The bosses' visual design is the crown jewel of the already outstanding work of the developers in this area. The map is huge, and the different areas are clearly distinct from one another in theme and ambience. Sometimes you need to move from one place to the other and the journey will be a bit too long. There are fast-travel portals and some other convenience-aimed devicesâ€”so the developers are aware of thisâ€”but maybe not enough. Still,  â€™ map is designed in a way that it allows for surprising shortcuts and interesting transitions. Also, be aware that there are lots of secret rooms. Sound edition is good. The music is nice, and helps set the proper dark ambience. Its main problem is, of course, that it becomes repetitive very quickly. This is a usual affliction of the genre, since they rely on infinite looping, and only extremely long tracks would solve the issue. Thereâ€™s much more to   that can be seen at first glance: a dark mythology based on distressingâ€”but detailed and unusual traditions. There is a lot of philosophy concerned between lines in this fantastical tale. What strikes me is the perspective of the reality that inspires the myth and fuels the story in the game. Maybe, like me, you will end up reflecting about the worldâ€™s values and the validity of beliefs. This is a triumph for a game like this; a breath of fresh air among many other half-baked, brain-dead platformers. A good game that dares to be bold and succeeds. It will suck your afternoon if you allow it to, in a fun way. Be prepared to die and repeat a lot of sections. I can't wait to see what these guys at The Game Kitchen are up to next. Piously recommended.", "appid": "774361", "steamid": "profiles/76561198071433169", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "41", "votes_funny": "1", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1575201600.0}
