{"text": "is a free-to-play and easy-to-learn turn-based puzzle game with nice logic and quite a bit of variety to keep the mind entertained. The puzzles are split into different Chapters, each having a number of puzzles in the campaign. You can move from one level to the next after you have solved the last one. Pretty soon after starting, you will be gradually introduced to the different modifiers that are present in this game, and you will have to recognize what they do and learn in order to progress, especially in later-on-levels. Your goal is to get to the exit (green cube) before the enemies blocks catch up to you. They can catch you on the exit block after you final move, so you do not get a free turn, even at the end. The modifiers include stun trap (loss of turns), switches or plates on the floors that alter another part of the level (color designated), teleporters (to a specific tile), mines, bombs, etc. There are also character power ups that give you extra moves, cow your enemies, or provide a shield. The enemy types are ones that follow you, to ones that mirror you or do just the opposite, there are ones that pace back and forth and also ones that move twice as fast as you do. If you win, you can move on. If you lose, you can easily reset the level and try again. In the early stages, it was very easy, a few seconds per level and pretty soon you feel like there's no challenge at all. But after a while, I ended up having to reset some levels a bunch to figure out my path to victory. There are still plans to add more content to the game itself, so that's nice of the developers to do, especially since it's a free game to start. It's nice that they are going to keep supporting it and making it better for current and future players. There is a level editor in this game, and since everything is predictable, it will be fairly easy for the player base to start crafting their own levels. I am not sure if the functionality is there in-game to share and view community content, though. So hopefully that's something that can be added if it's not already there. Mouse clicks work fine, you can zoom in and out with the scroll wheel, but the sensitivity on the scroll seems too low. You can also use WASD or Arrow keys to move the character around. I don't like isometric view + UP/Down/Left/Right controls that move the character in a diagonal. So I used a mouse. Simple graphics, works well for this game. Look at some screenshots, what you see is what you get. Nothing fancy here. Most people who enjoy logic puzzles will likely have fun with this. If you don't like puzzles, you can still try it, it's free after all. Can't really beat that it's a free game, with an internal level editor and developer plans for additional content.  +It's completely free +Good logic +Predictable enemy block motions +Variety in enemy types, block modifiers, character modifiers to keep the player thinking +Developers pay attention to player input and will work on making the game better -  (I was wrong, developer corrected me.) -Currently no V-sync  offers some fun and small-scaled logic puzzles in a sequence that keeps the game refreshing with its gradual introduction of new elements. Even though earlier levels may seem too easy, the later ones will keep you guessing from step to step. The inclusion of a level editor is nice, now just need to make sure that the community can share custom content with each other. Best of all, it's free, and the developers are planning to keep updating it with new content packages as well. Play the game, it's worth your time.", "appid": "1441570", "steamid": "profiles/76561198445832924", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "25", "votes_funny": "2", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1605096000.0}
