{"text": "This is a tough game to review, partly because it's very story driven and I don't want to go into spoiler territory, and partly because of the quality of the games that preceded it. That last point won't mean much to horror newbies, so I have to view it two ways: both as a fresh experience, and from the point of view of a perhaps more jaded perspective. This is going to be relatively straightforward.  For those who aren't over exposed to the horror genre, and are up for another bout of hide and seek, alternated with run like â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥, this is a great game. Dripping in atmosphere, with some genuinely unsettling sound effects and music, this is the work of masters when it comes to â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥ your pants ambience.  If you're looking to be scared then you're in the right place. For those who aren't new to the genre.......*sighs* well, this is going to depend on what you hoped for. Have Frictional Games improved from SOMA? Have they transcended the, IMO,  pinnacle of storytelling in the genre of spooky, first person, stealthy horror games?  Have they made revolutionary steps in the gameplay? Have they reasserted themselves as the top dogs after several strong contenders for the crown in recent (ish) years? (Outlast, Apsulov, Maid Of Sker etc) In short.....are you hoping this will rock your world? Because you could be ever, ever (ever!) so slightly disappointed if you'd hoped for a new wave of mechanics or approach to  what is now well worn schtick for the developers. What is here is done at a very polished level, and they haven't slacked off as such, since it's expertly crafted.  But it's also nothing new, beyond them doubling down on the narrative and greatly refining the environmental physics puzzles. More of the same but better, albeit depending on your stance as to whether more is better.  Don't like the monster avoiding gameplay? great - it's at least 2+ hours into the game before you even encounter one. So for a very long time it feels like the worlds most nerve wracking walking simulator, and can get a bit boring until it lets loose. When it lets loose it goes hard addressing the fact it's done â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥ all but smoke and mirrors up to this point, and if you wanted monster encounters then you've got 'em big time.  All that build up to make it all the more terrifying when you actually encounter something? It's either dull as â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥ or necessary legwork to give the monsters a deserved sense of menace.  The latter half of the game with it's noticeably relentless pacing of stealth and chase encounters? It's either a long overdue compensation to finally sink your teeth into something with intense action, or an inconvenience as you face yet another frustrating by-the-numbers sequence with only one viable way to play it..... i.e slowly Personally I'm in it for the frights and for the pant-â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥  gameplay, and so it was a bit of a barrier finding it's largely just the story up front with a few shocks for quite a long time. Though when the â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥ did finally hit the fan they've lost none of their touch at making pulse pounding tension, it's just that they're repeating familiar things by now, if you've played all of their games like I have.   Story-wise it's engaging, and really well told with great writing and voice-acting. I don't think that it was overall as fulfilling as SOMA' but there's no doubt they've stepped up a level with their ambition and creativity. The end result just didn't hit me as hard as SOMA, despite having some memorable moments where the morality of your actions comes into question. It's enjoyable, but doesn't quite work when you see it all at the end. Decent enough science fiction horror to be sure, yet this is the follow up to an absolute cracker and will not stay in the memory like that game does. As a game it has enough substance to keep my interest, albeit feeling like a walking simulator for a good few hours to begin with. The puzzles are nice to solve, the scares work, and it's fairly terrifying once they stop teasing you and actually have some enemy.  You can easily see they've got better in most departments, unless you wanted them trying something new. Because this is revolution, rather than evolution, it is the refinement that comes from this being their third iteration and the increase in their confidence and abilities. In a nutshell:  despite how polished and involving it is, it's still gameplay you've done many times before. I recommend it, as despite a few misgivings which hopefully I've detailed well enough for you here (albeit vaguely regarding the plot, so as to avoid spoilers) to decide if you want to jump in, I did enjoy my time with it.  Probably a boring as â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥ to read review, but I wanted to discuss it without giving anything away, as the story is still worth having its mysteries preserved. It just lacks a little when compared to the emotional and philosophical gut-punches its predecessor slammed you with.  If you gave yourself over to their previous games, then this should equally grab you. If, however, you have horror genre fatigue then this won't rejuvenate your interest. If you found this review to be helpful then why not check out my curator page here:", "appid": "999220", "steamid": "profiles/76561198250544676", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "59", "votes_funny": "1", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1603454400.0}
