{"text": "Notice: The first level starts out very slowly, it very much introduces the exploration and puzzle aspect of the game, but also introduces a bit of combat, so don't quit too early! The game picks up to be super wicked after, and the story gets explored too, especially at Map 6! Onto the review!: As the first of my friends to have obtained this game, I have a long journey ahead of me with no hints, tips or tricks. This review is based solely on my own impressions and observations. Overall I'd give the game a solid 9/10 Gameplay is amazing, really a good portion of the old-school with a good mix of Dungeons & Dragons with health potions and other items.  Though sometimes the exploration and puzzles draw out a bit, but the soundtrack is amazing and the level design is beautiful, so the little backtracking there is, is almost enjoyable actually... Almost. That's the only downside I can find. Soundtrack is a blast, ranging from calm tunes to wicked metal to some synthwave-like serene moments etc. A rush and a blast and a bit of calm for the soul, I love it. (I later found out that Zan actually licensed one of the original composers who made tracks for the original Unreal Tournament!) Visuals are absolutely a blast for a DOOM Engine game (I forgot the name of the game engine, \"id tech 1\" or something I guess?) The environments are gorgeous and the secrets are classy in an almost cheesy \"The cupboards might reveal a stash if you spam \"interact\" on them all!\" kinda way. The game has an extra difficulty called \"Bearzerk\" which is absolutely amazing, it is a melee-only mode and has 5 different melee weapons so far, including throwables etc. All items/consumables are still available. I recommend giving it a try after you've beaten the game on one of the base difficulties first, though! EXTRA: Do look out for secrets! Map 7 has a Bag of Holding! To anyone who does not play D&D: Permanent ammo capacity upgrades, like the backpack in DOOM. 3 different nodes in M