{"text": "I played   years ago and it was one of the best and most memorable   experiences. I'm glad, now after replaying it, that it's still the case. The game is rough around the edges, but it compensates its clumsiness and awkwardness with rich, thick atmosphere dripping with ancient, pagan, folk eeriness, evoking \"the old land steeped in blood and horror.\" I would say that the awkwardness even adds to the overall strangeness and spookiness. The Lost Crown is almost entirely made by one man, Jonathan Boakes, the creator of the   and is in the same universe. Unlike Dark Fall games which are first-person Myst clones, The Lost Crown is   (with some first-person sections). But it still retains that solitary feel of Myst like explorations with little hand holding. The game starts with arrival of Nigel Danvers to a small coastal English town, Saxton, rich with history, myth and legend and haunted by ghosts from the past. He ends up on the hunt for a mythical hidden treasure, the lost crown of an ancient king, meanwhile, investigating and releasing/exorcising ghosts.  The town of Saxton is fictional, but it seems to resemble real counterparts and the game uses actual locations around Cornwall for you to explore.   is shrouded in fog and drenched in mystery and paranormal phenomena that it looks like this whole area is a phantom-like entity summoned from the past. What I especially love is a sense that the ghostly hauntings are like a memory, an imprint of the time passed, like a recording in time and space that refuses to be forgotten and wants to tell you stories from those of personal tragedy and torment to those of epic myths and legends. There's also some temporal displacement going on and you're never quite sure    The eerie   is present even during the day when this sleepy town seems almost idyllic, but the vast windy landscapes under a stretched sky are beautiful and mysterious at the same time. They seem desolate, permeated with isolation and emptiness, but as one character said, \"the land is never empty.\" It's almost like they \"echo with voices of those that have gone before\" And then when the night falls, the pale moon rises to keep you company and follow you around, but not so much to light your way as to play tricks with light and shadow, deceiving your perception and teasing your imagination. This is when the spookiness intensifies which makes it the perfect time for ghosthunting, as the veil separating the living from the dead seems almost transparent during the witching hour.  Nigel often has an uneasy feeling that someone is watching him from the dark while he strolls through the empty streets at night or alone in the dark wood. But the creepiest and most unsettling parts are the Nite-Vision investigations, especially one in the church graveyard. This is when you switch to first-person view and suddenly your field of vision is greatly diminished. You feel limited and isolated by darkness since you can't use free roam, but a classic Myst-like point'n'click which is painfully slow only adding to the tension and   as you wait, while turning, for something to jump at you. Thankfully this game doesn't rely on cheap jump scares (there is only one), but builds its horror in that steady slow way that just creeps under your skin and stays with you long. Even though you can't die and there are no nail biting timed events (only two easy ones), the game succeeds in filling you with anxiety, dread and foreboding. That uneasy anticipation is especially heightened in Harbour Cottage, \"home sweet home\", the place where you sleep which is supposed to be a safe haven, but is actually the creepiest, oozing with dark, heavy, oppressive atmosphere. The excellent   greatly contributes to the spookiness with rattling tiles, creaking staircase, howling, whispers, footsteps - which have a slightly off-kilter sound so you're not quite sure if they're yours or from someone behind you. Background music is minimalistic and ethereal, not in your face but seamlessly woven with ambient sound effects to create rich otherworldly sound collages.   is also unique. The whole game is in black and white with occasional colourful accents (blue and especially red). This sometimes evokes the feel of those old faded washed up photographs which is another way the game creates (un)reality and a record of sorts. After May Day, the whole sky becomes clear blue while the land beneath is still grey making for an interesting symbolism.      Now, for this game to work its magic you need to have  . I mentioned at the start of my review that there's a certain clumsiness and awkwardness in execution which includes some technical shortcomings (like a fixed resolution and no widescreen support). The game is painfully slow - slow walk, slow talk, slow animations. You can fast travel on exits, but you can't speed up Nigel's stroll. There are strange pauses in dialog and a lot of repetitive lines: 'Nothing ventured', 'Symbolic images or ancient graffiti', 'That's not right' etc. Voice acting is mostly bad (with notable exceptions) especially Nigel. BUT, ironically, this awkwardness creates a kind of uncanny vibe that only heightens the general weirdness and an already eerie atmosphere, in the end working in its favour.  is a classic point and click. There are only a couple of hotspots per screen and they cover a wide area so there's no pixel hunting. Also your inventory isn't full of junk, but mostly consists of ghosthunting gadgets, ghost photos and EVP you've collected, also maps and notes to remind you what you're supposed to do. Speaking of ghosthunting gadgets, you're equipped with the E.M.F Meter, EVP recorder, Photo Camera and Nite-Vision Camera. EVP recordings are especially eerie, full of creepy sounds, scratching, howling, screaming (they sound even creepier when you know that some of them are real recordings).   are varied, from very simple to those hellish sound puzzles (like the organ, ugh). There's no real maze other than some maze like settings, but wondering around in the dark with limited night vision might count as one. So we have inventory puzzles, logic puzzles, dialog puzzles (the riddles). It's important to pay attention to what the characters are saying and there are quite a few quirky or bizarre npcs to talk to. Another well of information are the books, journals, articles you should read. Yes there is a lot of   in this game which I greatly enjoyed. Museum especially is full of information not only needed for puzzles, but for worldbuilding and story enrichment: old haunting tales, ghost stories, ancient myths, pagan rituals and holidays, folk wisdom etc. That's why I said patience is needed and taking your time to slowly soak everything in until you breath this ambience. The game is pretty long for an adventure, providing you don't use walkthrough (much) and read everything (which you should). Also, take notes, old school style   This steam version comes with achievements, but two of them are bugged (they work in the German version). This was supposed to be the first game in a trilogy that never came. I'm still waiting for the second one to come out. Still, recreating this kind of beautiful and unique experience is gonna be tough. But, nothing ventured...", "appid": "291710", "steamid": "profiles/76561198291108165", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "36", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1605096000.0}
