{"text": "First of all, this remains the most played game in my hours attained so far at this point. The fact remains that the sequel to the original Borderlands remained a instant hit after seven years never stops myself from playing it though. Borderlands 2's list of improvements and changes that have been brought up over years is quite ridiculous, and there is also the community patches as part of the modding enhancement and make sure to grab the Commander Lilith and the Fight for Sancturary considering the storyline skips to that DLC arc to where it all ends and begins for Borderlands 3.  [Edited: It's now in Steam, fantastic!] Here are the changes I have noticed from the original Borderlands to 2.  + Much more detailed and varied, enormous environments/locations and enemies, most areas such as Wildlife Explotation Preserve and Opportunity have their own distinctive music track and enemy or loot groups. + The randomized generated weaponry are obviously more powerful than the original, owning to the massive improvements that have been brought up during the transition to the Borderlands 2, and weapon parts play a major role to increasing gun/element damage and lessening the recoil, reload speed and much more.  + Higher levels, generally around a max of 90 with the combination of all major DLCs in Overpower Level 10 with 80 and it typically becomes more difficult as you enroach into the Ultimate Vault Hunter difficulty as the enemies can become more vulnerable to slag and other elements at the same time while their health are akin to being bullet sponges, it's best to keep that in mind the environment cover is your best friend for finding weaknesses.   + The learning curve can be a little steep, providing that you get started and get downed in the middle of a dangerous shoot-out. The modifiers for the badass rank can be attained over time as it actually changes the outcome of each combat engagement event as trivial if it's more than sufficient enough to disgorge some enemies with couple of shots.  + Six playable characters with Axton, Maya, Salvador and Zer0, with Gaige and Krieg as additional Vault Hunters, their skill trees and proficiency with specific weapons can be mentioned in their primary skills of interest. I usually find Axton and Gaige to be my overall favorites.  + The plot progression elements do exist in this series as the story keeps evolving as you move between all four games in sequence, and it's still not surprising that many familar characters are there and here at some point, Gluttony Gulch mentions a major plot point being finished after the Dragon Keep's DLC with Headhunter DLCs becoming the connecting link to what will follow as Lilith's Fight for Sancutary to where it ends.   + The gameplay is very much centered into trying to achieve their goals as Vault Hunters, as the part of the endless loot and shoot fest, as the enemies trigger their role of trying to reduce the Vault Hunter's health to 0 and it's your own job to keep these enemies out of the way, the usual resonance for FPS-type games most of the time. The amount of talking and interaction is much more higher than it is in BL1, due to the amount of supporting characters voicing their way to help each other in the time of the need in the wasteland planet Pandora, which is of course dangerous enough for visitors to get to the point of death rather quickly.  - Well, the claptraps are almost non-existent in BL2, save for the classic Fyrestone Claptrap that made it all the way by himself by pure luck, who knew they were quite annoying but funny to look at depending on the triggered hilariousness ensuing to their voices by messing things up by mistake. And also Handsome Jack is annoying as hell to be honest when it comes to his own way of toying around. - The legendaries are far less common than they are in the Borderlands previously, the grinding presents itself with some challenges of finding the specific weapon that you need to get and to get around that is to priortize the specific enemy's location and track that down and repeat it many times until you get it. The pearlscents are even more rarer, considering the fact they're all mostly very powerful in their downright, although improved in the community patches and doesn't change the evidence that their loot rates are very low and extremely rare to acquire, so special methods to get them is still needed to this day.  - Requires strategies that are usually considered into highest difficulty of UVHM, since the enemies are almost impossible to kill without slag weapons in the disposal. Trust me, you always will have to carry them when it comes to defeating various enemies that are tougher than normal. The chances are you're not going to like it when progressing but it's the part of the challenge in this game.  Besides the changes provided in this list, I can safely provide that it's well worth my recommendation to you within the boundaries of loot-shooting genre. It is still a masterpiece and always will be and I highly encourage you to give it a good try to see what works for you in the world of Pandora. The world of Borderlands is still big enough for anybody to get into it, and the chances are you just might like it in due process so I don't see why not.", "appid": "49520", "steamid": "profiles/76561198044426667", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "4", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1569240000.0}
