{"text": "Who the heck ever said, \"You know what this world needs? More GooCubelets. The first game wasn't enough; we need a sequel!\" Nobody, that's who. But I'm sure enough people said, \"Oh hey, I could use more cheap game trading cards, let's have GooCubelets 2 exist so we can farm them.\" It's probably those people that have pushed this monstrosity into existence. So thank you, card farmers. You're the ones who have brought GooCubelets 2 to the world of Steam. It's not like it needed more awful games, yet here we are. GooCubelets 2 either came to me in a bundle or at a heavily discounted price. I don't think I got it for free, though it's been given away several times. Whatever the price was, I got ripped off. It was another case of me thinking, in my youthful Steam mind, that good reviews for a puzzle game must mean it is a good game. Maybe I should have actually played GooCubelets before picking it up. Then again, perhaps they learned from their mistakes in GooCubelets. Maybe this sequel makes use of better mechanics and takes away my critiques of the original! Hahaha. Nope. I am still astonished at how much worse this game is than the first GooCubelets. I wrote a review for the first GooCubelets, and in that review is negative remarks about... well, almost everything. But then we get to this game and... whoo boy. Let's go step by step for what got even more messed up in the transition between the two of them. In GooCubelets, one of my few positive remarks was about how the music was decent. GooCubelets 2 scoffs at the thought of having good music and inserts one of the worst tracks I have ever heard as its first in the queue. The other tracks are forgettable at best. Great start, GooCubelets 2. Just endear me to you immediately by blasting that ridiculous theme through my headphones the moment your menu pops up. The graphics look the same as before. They still have bright colors against white backgrounds. Nothing is pretty to look at. It's tacky, and that's about the most generous term I can use for it. But to any of you worried about it, good news: the goocubelets still jiggle while moving. Speaking of movements, the physics in this game are even worse than in GooCubelets. I was not surprised to see that the developers stuck with Unity for GooCubelets 2, but they learned nothing about tightening up the slippery controls. Getting cubes trapped against walls without intending it happens far too often. To top this up, it leads to glitches. I had a fantastic moment where I pushed a red cube up to a block, and it proceeded to rocket off the stage into the atmosphere, thus resetting the whole stage. Thanks, I didn't need those five minutes of my life anyway. I'm not kidding about the time needed for the stages. GooCubelets had the courtesy to have mostly short stages. With most stages being about three to five minutes, GooCubelets 2 takes a lot longer and is a lot more annoying. It's especially frustrating when the game bugs out and you have to start from the beginning due to no fault of your own. Well, I guess it's your fault for playing GooCubelets 2, but I digress. There are two main gimmicks added into GooCubelets 2 that made me want to tear my hair out. The first is reversing your controls. If a cube goes over an arrow on the ground, your controls are reversed. If you go over another, your controls go back to normal. Each arrow only does this once. It has a silly MS-Paint-like X over it when you've activated it. Yet there is no visual cue to whether your controls are reversed or not, and a lot of levels have tons of these stupid things. For anyone insane enough to care about speedrunning this game, it might provide an interesting challenge. To the people who just want to beat the game (AKA me), it just makes long stages even longer. Then we get to the second gimmick, and I loathe it with a fiery passion. There are these \"black cubes\" that are placed in levels. If you or a cube you are moving touches the black cube, the level restarts. That would be fine if it was just a cube. But the area around it is also a no-entry zone. Combine this with the awful camera angles and distorted perceptions you have and it is extremely difficult to tell where the bloody thing will nuke you. If you even tilt slightly with your cube, rather than touching the contaminated square, whoops, still counts as you touching it. This has happened to me far too much. FAR too much. And you know what a simple solution would have been? Simply make all of the squares you can roll onto black ones. That would make it so easy to see where you shouldn't go. But nope, it's a guessing game, and if you're playing GooCubelets 2, you've already lost. Your reward for finally getting through all the levels? A credits screen you could have looked at any time from the main menu. AGAIN. A \"thanks for playing\" must have been too much effort for the developers. It's not worth grinding through fifty levels either way. The last level in particular is really long and really awful, just like in GooCubelets. There is still a timer, and you can beat specific times to get copper, silver, and gold medal things. The times are still ridiculous to try matching. I think these would be even worse to attempt than in GooCubelets given the absurd mechanics they added. I didn't bother trying to get any good times, and I think I got none of them by playing it naturally. Thank everything that the times are optional to beat. Oh, and there are typos. Typos in a game with barely any written sentences. There's a great accomplishment. If you want to get some extremely cheap trading cards, GooCubelets 2 is worth considering. If you want to play an actually good game, you won't find it here. You won't find it in the third game, either, because that one miraculously manages to become EVEN WORSE. I'm sure I'll go rant about it at some point, but I doubt anyone will see it, given that anyone wanting to play the games probably got scared away by GooCubelets or this game. I hope so, anyway. My sanity's about gone, but perhaps yours can still be saved by avoiding this series at all costs.", "appid": "416270", "steamid": "profiles/76561198040208524", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "20", "votes_funny": "4", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1479124800.0}
