{"text": "As a predecessor to the Fallout series, it is interesting, but I donâ€™t think it lives up to modern standards. Or early nineties standards. I tried getting into it, found it exceedingly tedious and decided to watch a good LP of it instead. This one: On the plus side, the Steam version is quite impressive. Despite the fact that it runs on DOSBox and itâ€™s not a full-on remake, the devs managed to add: And many more neat touches here and there. If you donâ€™t like these new additions, you can turn all of them off. I had no idea you could do something like that with DOSBox! But the game itself doesnâ€™t seem particularly well thought out. For example, the only reasonable way to heal after a fight is to wait. You can do that by holding Esc, but youâ€™ll be constantly attacked by random enemies appearing out of nowhere (even in towns). The thing is, if you hold   (for  iew) instead, the time will pass and youâ€™ll heal up with no enemies interrupting your rest. But in both cases it takes forever even if you use the built-in macro system. So, after each hard fight I ended up pressing F8 (macro for â‰ˆ120   presses in a row) around 10 or 15 times and alt-tabbing out for a few minutes. If I didnâ€™t do that, Iâ€™d get my butt kicked on the next random encounter. Hereâ€™s another example: use   on the ground, find a silver vein. Use a pick axe on the ground, loot the ground, get the cash (which doesnâ€™t weigh anything, by the way). Now make that into a macro and as long as you hold F10 or whatever, youâ€™ll get   money. Jammed the key, went AFK for around 10 minutes, came back to find $20000+ in my pockets. Is this an exploit? I think I was using the   skill exactly as it was intended. Itâ€™s not my problem that the devs forgot to add code for the silver vein to actually run out. Anyway, what led me to uninstall the game in the end was the fact that the combat was so boring. Most of the time you just press   4 to 6 times, confirm with   and repeat that until the fight is over. And random encounters are so frequent, you can hardly cross a street without getting pounced on by something. I ended up fast forwarding through some fights without reading the combat log in detail, didnâ€™t notice one of my characters getting hurt, carried on. By the time I reached the next town the guy was dead dead. And of course the game has already autosaved on it, overwriting the only existing save.", "appid": "259130", "steamid": "profiles/76561197992892379", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "37", "votes_funny": "3", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1512043200.0}
