{"text": "*Rant of a jaded old fart incoming who clearly forgot how to have fun* I like to imagine a Bethesda board meeting where they were going \"I don't know, there has to be a way to waste even more of the player's time\". Do you like smithing 2,000 Gold Rings to get your smithing skill up? Do you enjoy killing trivial enemies over and over to fill your sould gems for enchanting? Does the mere thought of running mindless errands and doing uninspired fetch quests cause you to just cream your pants? Do you sometimes think \"Man, I wish this game was even grindier\"? Then by golly is this the DLC for you! First things first: Hearthfire lets you build a house. So far so good. Now you can have a house in every hold except Winterhold, which is, apart from the Mage's College, mostly a deserted eyesore anyway. You start off with building a Small house that you can then augment with a main hall. Once you've done that you can build up to three wings on your house where you have a choice of three options for each. East Wing can be an Armory, Kitchen or Library, North Wing can be made into a Trophy Room, Storage Room or Alchemy Laboratory, while for the West Wing you have the choice between Bedrooms, Greenhouse and Enchanter's Tower. You want a house with Library, Kitchen and Bedrooms? Game says \"No, go â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥ yourself!\". And that's where customisation ends, as will become evident. To build the different parts you have to select them at the drafting table and then click on the different stages at the carpenter's workbench, while having the required resources in your inventory. Resources mainly consist of Iron parts (fittings, hinges, nails), lumber, clay and quarried stone, with added corundum for door locks for whatever reason.  Now the building becomes a glorified game of \"click all the options\" at the workbench and a mindless grind for resources. You go to the different towns, buy every Iron Ingot you can come across, forge them into nails, visit the lumber mill for wood where the vendor uses the same generic line over and over \"Doing some building, eh? I'll have them hauled over right away!\", wait for your character to mine clay and stone, go back to workbench, click click click, oh no more nails left, forge more nails, click click click, back to the lumber mill, and to town because you ran out of iron, click click, oh damn I forgot to buy corundum, click click forge more nails click click and forge some more bloody nails. With each click you add a new component of the part you're building, foundation, walls, door, roofing, etc. Since there's no actual building this isn't fun in the slightest. I suppose you're meant to build a few parts when you can between adventures and see your house slowly grow over time. Experience teaches us that that is not what gamers do, though. Now to the interior design. Each part can of course be furnished, which again needs resources, some of which like glass are quite hard to come by (because of course they are. Wouldn't be Skyrim if you didn't have to suffer for your accomplishments). For every piece of furniture you have two options: Build and don't build. You cannot choose where to put the bed, you especially cannot choose between different kinds of beds, you can just choose to either have a bed or not have a bed. Either have a shelf there or stare at a blank wall. Maybe it's for the best, since customisable placement would probably be too much for the game's physics engine to handle. An engine that to this day doesn't allow you to place objects into display cases unlesss you want said items to spawn outside of the case the next time you enter your home. Luckily you can hire a steward and pay him or her a stipend to furnish the different parts for you over time. I certainly couldn't be arse at that point anymore. Then you can finally move in with your spouse, who will then â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥ about how unsafe this region is. Fun. Also you can adopt children with this DLC. Whatever, there's little to no depth to that. Also this DLC will unlock more mindless busywork pertaining to your home such as a Giant's attack oder a Skeever infestation. Not exactly fun, but maybe something to count down the hours till you die. One little positive thing I have to add is that the houses you build are vastly superior to every house you can buy in the vanilla game. That's not saying much, though. TL;DR: Hearthfire is not the Sims in Skyrim experience people have lauded it as. Different layouts? No. Different styles of wallpaper or furniture maybe? Nope. Different placement options for items? â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥ no! You get one thing and you will like it because we're Bethesda and we don't care. I've harped on Skyrim a lot and the #1 defense I always get from fanboys is \"Just install mods it fixes everything\". And for once I have to agree. There's probably a mod out there that gives you the house building experience you were looking for. So get that instead of this insult of a DLC.", "appid": "220760", "steamid": "profiles/76561198027358460", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "55", "votes_funny": "15", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1490184000.0}
