{"text": "I'll say this right off the bat, if you're planning to play this with friends then this review doesn't apply to you. During the free open beta when I played this with my friends, I had a blast. So if you've got friends who are willing to play Steep with you then go for it, it's a great game for that. But if none of your friends own Steep and you're stuck playing solo... well... it's a bit more complicated. I won't lie, the first 5-10 hours of Steep are nothing short of pure magic. Whether you're doing tricks, or opening that sweet wingsuit for the first time, or gliding down a mountain for fun, or playing around with the impressive amount of customization, there's really no better word to describe the experience than \"magic\". But as you do those things for the second, third, fourth time the magic begins to wear off little by little, every time. And then, in an instant, you'll come to the realization that the game is just... boring. Nothing ever changes in the game. Sure, the challenges get tougher and the slopes get steeper, but it's really not that different from what you were doing 1 hour, 2 hours, or 5 hours ago. Sure, the devs added a few new smaller maps in, but they feel more like reskinned chunks taken from the main map than fresh new slopes. Look, if you think you can get over the repetitiveness of the game then go for it. I'd be super happy if I could have that \"magic\" for 100 hours rather than 10, but for the average person, you'll most likely find this game to be too repetitive. Shame, really.", "appid": "460920", "steamid": "profiles/76561198056828997", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "6", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1499169600.0}
