{"text": "If you've seen the screenshots, then you already know the main attraction of   its grainy, washed-out, grindhouse visuals. Coupled with the sparse, twanging guitar soundtrack and knowingly corny use of occult symbols (the melee crosshair, for example, is shaped like a pentagram for no other reason except that it  ), there's a uniquely gutbucket sensibility to the game that makes the first thirty minutes or so a memorable dive into the bowels of the Steam bargain bin. After that, however, the novelty of   aesthetic can no longer paper over the sub-par game design. It's a first-person shooter in which the \"fire\" button doesn't always work, enemy design lacks variety (almost all of them use melee attacks or fire the same green pellets at you), battles take place in open spaces with little opportunity to use the environment to your advantage, and the lack of checkpoints means you'll lose fifteen minutes' worth of progress if you make a bad jump and fall into the insta-death abyss. One level in particular -- with inadequate supplies of ammo, copious opportunities to fall to one's death, and uninteresting battle design emphasizing long-distance shooting -- took me a week to motivate myself to complete, because the slog just didn't seem worth the investment of mental energy. Come for the visuals, leave when you get bored of the gameplay.", "appid": "731590", "steamid": "profiles/76561198022425833", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "5", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1518091200.0}
