{"text": "Imagine performing surgery within a claw-crane toy vending machine.  The surgeon's single hand is, by design, one of the clumsiest manifestations of inter-activity ever published.  Of course this would be the very point and what makes it so much fun! The difficulty in getting anywhere because of this intentional disconnect with user input can, however, be frustrating at times.  I personally require a mouse pad the size of Central Park in order to move the arm around (even on the highest sensitivity).  It's definitely presented as a joke game, not an achievement or skill game, although those things are very much required to get anywhere.  There is no advice or direction in how to approach a given surgery, lots of bloody fun in the trial and error.  Too difficult to grasp objects in general, it can take an eon to get the scalpel in your hand at the right angle for incision.  Certainly not realisitic, and the title \"simulator\" here must be taken with a grain of salt.  Or a salt mine even.          On the positive, I totally knew what I was getting into and got a deal on the game anyway, so it's no travesty that's happened here.  The game really is pretty funny, and that seems to be it's greatest achievement.  I had  dreams of a more balanced mix of sim and parody...but got mostly the latter.            If  the hand were SLIGHTLY more dexterous, I would've enjoyed it more.  I'm sure it must be rewarding for true mouse-keteers that eventually hone their precision with the movements... that seems the only way to advance passed the first surgery even.  When the difficulty in progressing becomes more frustrating than fun, a game generally loses me.", "appid": "233720", "steamid": "profiles/76561198116819753", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "41", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1388059200.0}
{"text": "Changing my recommendation after the recent issues of a Founder having their account banned for black market traders slipping through DE's fingers.  They are currently holding someone's account hostage if they trade items with someone who uses \" black market \" platinum. This person didn't know about the black market trader and has had their account locked until they pay around 4000 platinum back to DE for literally nothing. Link below to the thread. The community moderators have locked the thread to prevent it from getting any further attention. This is a predatory, disgusting, and unprofessional practice and makes me regret being a founder of the game back in 2013.  This is not ok, no matter what kind of account it is. They lose literally nothing by letting this person keep access to their account, but instead they'd rather punish someone who's done nothing wrong. They've also tried to bury the story by hiding it in an \" off topic \" area on the forums to prevent it from showing up in more trafficked areas. On top of all this, there's still no way to earn cosmetics in game without spending money, or earn warframe and weapon slots without spending money.  Catalysts and Reactors for Weapons and Warframes to double your mod capacity are intentionally held under a timed knife and only rarely offered to the community, meaning that if you aren't able to jump online at the drop of a hat you'll most likely be missing a majority, if not every single one of them.", "appid": "230410", "steamid": "profiles/76561198044912477", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "1", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1377345600.0}
