{"text": "To quote Yngwie Malmsteen, \"how can less be more? More is more\"... I love puzzles. I love gorgeous indie artwork and stories about friendship. So how did this game make me want to stab my own eyes out with a fork? 1. The story. Our two characters are wordless, and the reward at the end of each level is pretty much a still of them hanging out. I found it boring, and that's coming from someone who plays a lot of visual novels/walking simulators. 2. The speed. If a game is to be based entirely around rewinding time, PLEASE for the love of god let me do it more quickly than this. It feels like the slow walking speed has been implemented on purpose to stop you realising how short the game actually is. 3. The puzzles Puzzle difficulty is inconsistent. I feel like good game design leads you into understanding the mechanics before forcing you to try a harder version of the same, whereas this game asks you to just walk around more, ignoring the tools you have, until you solve the level almost by accident. 4. The music I muted it a few mins in because the ETERNAL string notes underneath everything felt \"busy\". 5. That pricetag. I got this on sale for ~Â£4, so overall it was worth the experiment, but if I'd paid full price I'd definitely be annoyed. Positives: + A very nice consistent art style + An interesting concept, albeit poorly executed", "appid": "600990", "steamid": "profiles/76561198042965861", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "17", "votes_funny": "2", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1584187200.0}
